<AbstractNarration>0224729&lt;br/&gt;Hadjicostis&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;The main goal of this research project is to develop a comprehensive&lt;br/&gt;framework for dynamical state estimation, fault detection and fault&lt;br/&gt;accommodation in energy processing systems.  Such systems include&lt;br/&gt;terrestrial and autonomous power systems, electric drives and power&lt;br/&gt;electronic systems, and can be found in both civilian and military&lt;br/&gt;sectors.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;The PI's approach is based on a  family of experimentally verifiable and&lt;br/&gt;mutually consistent dynamic models, with various family members being&lt;br/&gt;suitable for different tasks in analysis, fault management and&lt;br/&gt;control. In addition to exploring hierarchical and distributed&lt;br/&gt;architectures for monitoring and accommodating for faults in energy processing&lt;br/&gt;systems, he will also study simulation environments in which multiple&lt;br/&gt;models with embedded redundant dynamics are used to detect&lt;br/&gt;inconsistencies, and to initiate more detailed  simulations to resolve&lt;br/&gt;them. He will also study economic and environmental aspects of fault&lt;br/&gt;tolerance in energy processing systems.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
